"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, I want to talk about crumb structure. Crumb structure is what allows high quality, good living, biologically churning soil to hold more water and more air than dead, beat up old soil. And the reason is is that the microbes in the living soil are busy bonding. Well, see, when they break everything down, that the finest level they turn everything into like a weird paste. And everything gets clumped together with this paste. It becomes a weird glue. Like if the only thing you could make a house out of would be bricks, then this goo would be like the cement. And it bonds all the inorganic particles to the organic particles and makes these big clumps of things, and these big clumps of things have more space between them. Just like uh if you like have a big box and you fill it full of sand, it won't hold that much water. But if you filled it full of like baseballs or bowling balls or some really large size, it would hold lots of water and lots of air. There'd be lots of space between those bowling balls. And so that's the same way with crumb structure, is that it's going to hold more of everything that the soil needs. It needs not just the water, which will hold a lot more, and that's great, but needs the air. And so that's a great way to kind of augment all the nice things that will be happening in your soil if it's soft, if it has good crumb structure, because this crumb structure, this biological goo is weak. It's strong enough to break up water, it's weak enough for roots to go right through it. So it has to be a real kind of fine, nice, easy to break up quality, and that gives it like a soft texture. But again, crumb structure, okay. Other than just you know, being cool about soil and all, crumb structure is a great name for uh um hardcore band, either metal or punk, I'll give it to you. And just think about the longer you think about, the better it becomes. Crumb structure. Oh, and by the way, if you have a better hardcore band name 